segments.text: Office of Debbie Messing Hamlin, and this is the 15th of March, 1985.
And we're here to discuss with Debbie her role in the department.
So, Debbie, let me just double.
Okay, I'm the Community Development Administrator for the city, and I've been with the city about 10 years, and I have a master's in planning.
I started out with the planning department 10 years ago,
And I did general planning for about three or four years under Mr. Cunningham.
And then when grants were introduced to the city, I transferred laterally.
And I've been working with community development block grants ever since, including EDAG grants, economic development grants, whatever kind of grant programs that we happen to administer.
Okay, Debbie, I've been talking with Nestor, and he's answered some of these questions already.
But I wanted to ask you what the role of private planning consultants has been in El Paso's development.
Okay.
We've retained two major consultants in the last few years.
For our downtown plan, we've retained American Cities Corporation, which is a subsidiary of the Rouse Corporation.
They came in and prepared a downtown implementation plan for the city.
And with that plan, we were able to generate a UDAG for our downtown.
And that included a $6 million UDAG for the revitalization and restoration of two major buildings.
One will be a downtown hotel, the other a major office building.
Both of them are National Register properties, and they generate about $40 million worth of private sector money.
And that's the first major... What's the name of the hotel?
The Paso Del Norte Hotel and the Cortez Office Building.
We remember the Paso Del Norte Hotel because we had you arranged, essentially, the AIP conference there for the Texas chapter in 19... Oh, gosh, it's been about 1979.
79, was it?
Or 78, something like that.
And that one will be totally restored.
And right next to it will be constructed a 20-story tower, which will be designed in the old style to complement the Paso Morning Hotel.
And then the Cortez office building, which is also a Trost National Register property, will be restored into office and parking garage.
That is essentially the first major
development, public-private partnership downtown, and we're hoping it'll spur on more development downtown.
We also have retained Zuckelly Hunter, which is Z-U-C-H-E-L-L-I, Hunter Consultants, to prepare a downtown revitalization project.
plan and program for implementation in downtown Isleta, which is in our lower valley.
That's an area that was incorporated into the city about 50 or 60 years ago and has some of the oldest missions and some of our oldest history in El Paso, the Tegua Indians and so on.

We also retain the housing, the Historical American Buildings Survey crew out of Washington a couple of years ago did a mission trail study which goes down into our valley and some of the information that the killing hunters use, they'll be using from the Habs people.
Where is the Sukelle 100 firm located?
I keep wanting to think they're out of Boston, but I think they're also out of somewhere around Maryland.
They're out of the East Coast.
East Coast.

In both cases, the city looked around and did a request for proposals to research which firms would be the best suited for El Paso, and we're hoping that we'll be able to implement some of their recommendations out of both studies.
We since, I should say, retained American Cities again since the downtown master plan to do a remarketing study for downtown El Paso.
We've been hurt very badly by the Paso devaluation and our retailers are asking that they be helped to understand what the market really is now and to possibly remarket their
their businesses for better retail.
So we're working with them to do that.
We're also waiting for Ralph to come to El Paso in March.
Oh, this March, this month.
There will be a public announcement after that as to whether or not Ralph will be committing to El Paso further to possibly bring a large retail component to our district.
We'll see what happens there.
And then you mentioned the planning department has...
Yes.
We have funded, the community development program has funded $50,000 to the planning department to update their comprehensive plan.
And I believe that the city is also matching that share.
And hopefully they'll be retaining a consultant.
I don't believe they have any, but they'll be retaining a consultant to do an update.
Okay.
Going on to the next question, about the five or so major events that have affected El Paso's planning and the development of El Paso.
I think the Chamizal Treaty was a major development in El Paso, rerouting the river
and causing changes to the land use and development to El Paso space.
And that's been 15 years, I guess, or 20.
That's C-H-A-M-I-Z-A-L treaty.
Mr. Cunningham was the major force in that treaty.
Like I said, it did reroute the river through El Paso.
I understand most of the land had to be given to Mexico.
Yes, a lot of it did.
There was a lot of relocation of homes also.
That was during President Johnson's administration?
Yeah, President.
He came to El Paso during that time.
Oh, he did visit El Paso as president.
Yeah, so did Kennedy right during that.
It was right during the Kennedy-Johnson.
Uh-huh.
And they created a monument for Kennedy over there.
They think he's quite impressive.
I see.
They equated him sort of to Lincoln, so they have, I guess they, yeah, they did have two presidents.
Two special movements between them at the same time.
Another big, I guess, I think change has been the takeover of the more national banks over our local banking industry here in El Paso.
And that probably was looked upon originally as a negative takeover because people like to keep their things home.
But I think it will be a good injection into the El Paso economy.
very concerned about the downtown.
They want to see it prosper.
And they seem to be interested in working with private and public
parties to try and inject money into El Paso for that purpose.

I think another big change has been the development of the north-south and east-west freeways in El Paso and they have spurred development in both directions and the land use has definitely changed along both those routes.
There was a major amount of course of relocation to perform both of those
developments, but they have changed, like I say, especially in the eastern part of El Paso where it was all desert and there was really no way to get downtown to the west side.
Um, way past Fort Bliss and out toward, um, I guess that's I-10.
Um, and then I think,
What was the other thing you were talking about?
Fort Bliss.
Fort Bliss, right.
Fort Bliss used to be a major base in El Paso, and then they cut way down.
They didn't have their basic training here anymore, and it really hurt our economy.
It appears now that the government's decided to go ahead and reenact that basic training element and also train a lot of foreign military here in El Paso.
So that will be a big injection of the economy.
OK.
Anything else?
One thing I need to mention, and you probably will share this a little bit more, is the development of our mountain, which has been a major impact on El Paso space.

We've had a lot of controversy about how to develop it and the city has been looking into a lot of other cities as to how they develop their mountain areas and there's been a lot of scarring of the mountain because there wasn't good planning in the beginning.
There's been a lot of anxiety to the, you know, to El Paso's
El Paso has a lot of pride in the mountain.
We'd like to keep it as it is.
Of course, it's in the hands of private ownership, so we have developed a new mountain development ordinance and so on to try and regulate it as best we can.
We're trying to do that now.
Where is the wilderness area?
The wilderness park, you can see it from here.
It's actually the Franklin Mountains.
This is the western side.
As we look from City Hall to the mountain, the Wilderness Park area is really on the eastern side of the mountain.
And it was an estate swap, basically, for that land to become Wilderness Park.
Part of that mountain is now hidden in the clouds, but that wilderness park is at the very top.
Some 200, I don't remember how many acres of that there is, but probably Nestor could tell you that.
When you think a minute about events caused by governments and so forth at the national level or the state government,
or Mexico in your case, what events have influenced planning in El Paso, if any?
One event that has been a major implication is really the discussion of water and how it's going to affect El Paso's future.
And I think the state of New Mexico and the state of Texas have been in litigation for some time now about the usage of their bolsons and so on for El Paso's water.
And some of the latest litigation has ended in El Paso's favor, but it's being contested.
And this time, you know, we're very concerned because water is...
is supposedly going to be depleted in the next 30 or 40 years here.
And that will definitely impact on El Paso's future development.
So that has been one big state type of involvement we've been involved in the last two years in a major way.
As far as Mexico goes, the peso devaluation has impacted us tremendously.
Negatively, it has.

both from the retail market that I described earlier and also in the fact that it's put a lot more people into El Paso, probably illegally and legally, trying to get to the United States to work because they've been hurt tremendously over there.
I've heard that to work in their...
industry for one week, they may get $3 of American money.
So they're coming over here in droves trying to find employment, which is impacting our own employment, which is extremely high, let's say 11%.
We can't get our own people jobs, and we've got a lot of people from Mexico coming over here seeking employment also.
That's neat.
What administrative procedures and planning program elements does El Paso have for implementing community plans?
Can you sort of give me some... For example, you have a separate department now here.
That certainly is an administrative procedure that is different from most communities.
Is it?
I wasn't...
I don't know how... Yeah, I guess it is different.
Basically, yeah, we're a separate department.
We try and tie in, of course, with planning as much as we can.
They perform the long-range planning.
We perform the short-range annual planning, pretty much.
We are not involved at all in the subdivision and land use aspect.
Strictly, we're looking at redevelopment of our older areas and to make them more viable neighborhoods.

We're also involved in the economic development end of it, in that we have several economic development revolving loan funds here, which we're trying to provide the gap financing to small businesses that need financing that they can't get from the banks.
And as we see, one of our main functions here and our goals is to try and increase the employment aspect.
So we're working toward that.
How many professional planners does El Paso have employed as part of city staff?
That is to say, planners with planning degrees and so forth.
In this department, I'm the only one.
We have about 35 people employed here.
And I was like an offshoot from planning department, so I'm just an implant.
The planning department, let's see, I think they probably have, with planning degrees or related urban study degrees, maybe they have five or six.
That's all.
What future direction do you see El Paso's planning efforts taking in the next 10 years?

I think we're all hoping that we can do more redevelopment of our inner city, and we're also hoping that we can maybe do more infill development in our older areas, rather than continuing to do the sprawl, which is where we've been headed.
El Paso has grown tremendously fast in the last 20 years.
I mean, I talked to our traffic engineer two days ago about traffic problems, and he related something to me that's kind of interesting.
We were talking about the need to create Loop 72, 372 around the city because we have some traffic problems.
I said, well, what kind of traffic problems do we have?
He goes, well, for instance, in 1962 on Montana Street,
We had like 82,000 cars, and now we have 210,000.
So, I mean, we have a tremendous amount of growth that's occurred in El Paso in a short time.
I believe it's because we're a Sunbelt city.
On the other hand, we haven't been able to get a handle on our pollution problems, and we haven't been able to get a handle on our growth problems, which are seeming to spread in all directions.
So I think we're probably going to be hoping to...
do more and better planning in our own inner city area and get a handle on all the illegal subdivision growth going on on the outside, more control, subdivision and zoning.
Does the Planning Commission support staff in these matters?
They have been pretty supportive, I think.
And the council?
The council, yeah.
I think the council has been.
We have a very strong mayor right now that is from the land development community.
He is one of the major property owners in the city.
He was also the president until last year of one of the largest mortgage-making industries in El Paso.
And his name?
Jonathan Rogers.
So he has been a very pro-development but good development man, and I think it's been good for El Paso.
What was the name of the mayor that Jonathan Cunningham worked so closely with?
He was in office for so many mayors.
I guess John Henderson, Fred Hervey.
Fred Hervey was the mayor twice when he was in office.
And he paved the first streets.
I mean, I think probably it would be Fred Hervey.
And he was very active in the development.
And he still is a major mover in the development community.
El Paso has a strong mayor form of government.
That sometimes is very difficult for the planning function of local government to work with.
Are there any moves toward city managers for El Paso or not, and how do you think that might eventually work itself out?
I think in the last year, the city just created a new position under the mayor called the Executive Administrator or Assistant.
And that is right now filled by Dr. Kenneth Beasley.
Where does he come from?
He comes from the university system.
And the mayor brought him in when he was elected, Mayor Rogers did.
And he has created that very strong position in salaries in the $60,000 range.
And that is the first time we've ever had a funded position of that kind.
And he acts sort of like a city manager, but he is not called a city manager.
And I think he doesn't really have exactly the powers of a city manager.
I don't think El Paso will move in that direction only because we've seen cities around El Paso like Las Cruces that have gone through many city managers, and they're smaller.
It's a much smaller city than El Paso, 40,000, 50,000 population.
I think we've seen historically that cities that...
have the nature of the population we have around, approaching half a million, I mean, yeah, 500,000, half a million now, that they don't really work well in cities that big.

And I'm not sure El Paso will move in that direction, although, like I say, we sort of, this is the first, this is now, we're moving into our second or third year with this particular kind of individual in that position, and it has worked pretty well.
He is...
The mayor has relied on him heavily to make administrative decisions and has told the department heads that they are to go to him and solve all their problems before they ever get to him.
So he's sort of acted in that capacity, but has not really called that or have the same sort of powers as the city manager has.
Does he have authority over personnel?
Yes and no.
He works extremely close with the personnel department and the personnel director.
He has helped to
shape the change of the new city charter.
So there has been some influence, yet I'm not real sure the nature.
How strong is a city manager tied to that?
Do you know, Bob?
Usually the city manager is in charge of all personnel.
Okay, he, no, he doesn't.
With the exception of the city attorney.
Okay, the city personnel director here is still very strong and runs the city personnel department.
But like I said, this individual does work very strongly with you.
So there is some similarity there, but not clear-cut.
And I don't think that when the new city charter changes just were passed by the overall city last year, they did not incorporate that change into it.
the city charter, so I don't know if we're going to be going in that direction anymore.
I sort of doubt it.
El Paso has quite a long history of comprehensive city-wide planning.
Do you see that changing?
I do.
I do.
I think that the city is really moving toward more of an implementation planning.
I mean, I think that the long-range plan is important.
But I think we're seeing that it can't be that long range.
The time frame is going to have to be reduced.
I think it probably will have to be reduced.
That's my opinion.
I think that when we look at what is realistic now and what we really need to shoot for, I think the longer range plans are becoming that effective or haven't been that effective in the past.
So I would see a move away from that.
Has the policies of the Reagan administration, have they had any effect on El Paso's planning and development?
I think if they're implemented the way he wants them, they'll have major disastrous effect on the city.
For instance, in revenue sharing, El Paso, in the last few years, has used their revenue sharing monies, most of them for operational rather than capital improvements, 97%.
So if they were to be cut, it would affect us disastrously in the operational.
area of the city and how it runs.
Another good example of how it would affect El Paso, if they cut CDBG money.
out totally, which is not looked at.
They're not looking at doing that.
But for instance, if they did, we are right now representing half of the city's capital improvements budget.
If it's $15 million, we're representing half of it right now.
That would hurt us tremendously.
They're not looking at doing that.
They're looking at maybe a 10% or 20% cut.
It would still affect a major effect.
We have been increasing our taxes slowly in El Paso, but historically we have not been a big proponent of raising taxes substantially.
We're a relatively very poor city.
compared to most other Texas cities.
For instance, in our own program here, we have many houses a year.
We spend about $2 or $3 million annually.
We have homes of families that have less than $4,500 incomes.
So we have not historically been a city that's raised taxes.
So we may have to start looking at that or some alternative bond issues or something else to raise money to do capital improvements if Reagan's
plans to cut us federally come through.
So it will hurt us tremendously.
Can you think of any additional thoughts that might affect El Paso's future in terms of the direction it takes in planning?
This is the second part of the interview with Anne Cunningham.
Anne, regarding the major individuals who instigated or strongly affected El Paso's planning programs,
Could you recall some of these individuals and also indicate in what way they affected planning in El Paso?
I do remember two outstanding chairmen of the City Planning Commission that served with John very well and contributed so much of their time and thoughtfulness and genuine
unselfishness to the cause of city planning.
The two men I remember

distinctly are Mr. Herbert Swartz of the popular department store who gave up so much of his time and even some of his property to develop a downtown little park to beautify the city and served judiciously and well as a planning commissioner and director of the planning commission.
Do you know what period that was?
What years?
I can't recall the years, but they could be researched.
Another good gentleman who served with distinction was Mr. Leonard Goodman.
He and Jonathan worked so well together and did accomplish
so many fine decisions with the help of a good commission at the time.
Two fine mayors that I recall.
One, Judson Williams, a man that Jonathan felt was a fine administrator, willing to take responsibility, make decisions, and then put them into effect.

He also enjoyed working with Burt Williams, who was a flamboyant and fun mayor, and yet a mayor with a great deal of courage, a mayor unlike any other mayor I believe in the United States had the courage to sue a circle for polluting the city.
Remember Burt Williams?
Yes, didn't he have his own airplane?
I don't remember that.
That would fly here and there?
I don't think Burt had an airplane, to my knowledge, but he may have.
One of the mayors had that John was very close to.
Really?
I'd forgotten that detail.
Now, there were some good women on the planning commissions, too.
I shouldn't overlook their names.
And forgive me for not remembering them right now.
Well, you can write them in later on when I send you the transcription.
All right.
OK.
Think a minute of about the half dozen most important events that have occurred in El Paso in terms of planning.
Just briefly enumerate them.
Well, I think always of the Shamizal National Memorial Park as a cultural center for the city, funded and helped by the federal government.
Then I think of the interstate freeway development system that Jonathan worked so diligently to get rooted properly through the city with

the greatest amount of efficiency and beauty in other words he made an underpass under the city rather than put put the interstate up high on stilts over the city so that it would not detract from the city skyline and he was proud of that fact now the other planning events
in El Paso.
We've already mentioned the park system.
And then you had some reference to the school.
Oh, I think whenever the public schools, community college, and UT El Paso asked Jonathan for advice for site planning or site additions or genuine concerns about planning parking space or
extending their genuine areas to be more serviceable to the community.
Jonathan willingly studied these situations as carefully as he could and gave them good advice.
In fact, many of the school locations, community college locations, were suggested by Jonathan and they have turned out to be useful and
efficient.
Would you care to recall the selection of the location for the Civic Center?
That I do remember.
John felt that it should be, of course, accessible primarily for people living in all sections of this city.
And his site selection downtown
easily entered by people from east, northeast, west El Paso via the interstate, is fine and has turned out to be the best possible location that a civic center could have for a city of our size.
It was quite controversial before it was constructed.
At the time, many did criticize the site.
yet it was acquired within the economic bounds of the city's ability, and it also geographically, and from the point of view of accessibility, as I said before, was just fine, and it still is.
The railroads.
In the Kessler Plan, George Kessler,
Noted in 1925, or actually it was before that, that the railroads had numerous grade crossings with downtown streets, and the plan called for their eventual removal.
As I understand it, John moved as best he could to implement that proposal, the original proposal.
plan for El Paso.
Yes, he did feel that the railroads did detract from the downtown area and moved to have them put underground and wanted them not to obstruct the transportation within the city.
I remember he had many, many meetings with the directors of the railroads that came into El Paso, too.
see if grade crossings could be better for the use of the city residents, and at the same time not destroy the efficiency of the railroads.
Okay.
John was continually working for the good of his staff to get better quarters.
And they moved from the old abandoned Safeway store on Ochoa Street to a new city hall where they weren't in a separate building, isolated from the rest of the official city family.
Yet the Safeway building was really updated and made into a fine office building for his staff by Mr. Joe Hamra.
It was one of the most efficient buildings
beautifully planned, planning buildings I've ever seen.
It was perfectly located.
Are we in to this now?
We're taping.
It had a conference room.
It had a small map room, perhaps not large enough.
Good design quarters.
Excellent reception desk.
With Mrs. Mendez behind it.
Miss Mendez.
Miss Mendez.
Who was his administrative assistant.
A very efficient office manager, if ever there was one.
So I understand.
And a fine translator of Spanish, and a fine correspondent in Spanish when Jonathan had to communicate with
officials in Mexico City, by the way, over the Chamizal transfer of land.
The Civic Center, the Convention Center, the schools, the railroad, Chamizal, carrying out the recommendations of the
1925 plan, having it updated periodically.
What about the mountain, Franklin Mountain?
Oh, he did.
He did really work hard to preserve, I believe, the mountain beauty of this area.
Although there was much criticism from the current place

residence uh jonathan held off the development of crazy cat mountain i believe so that his um delaying process at least kept that development from getting off the ground for a while but as he always pointed out the man who owns the land eventually will develop it uh with um
enough determination in about the way he wants to develop it.
And Crazy Cat Mountain is being developed now in accord with certain planning regulations, but it has had many opposing factions, especially in the current place.
Now, the Wilderness Park and the Guadalupe's was an interest of John's too,
When Lady Bird Johnson came to the area, he and some people from the Interior Department did spend a few days down there on the Wilderness Park.
And he was intensely interested in Tom May's park, too, in the county.
His interest in planning extended beyond just the mere boundaries of the city.
And he did work with the county commissioners on some of their plans for park development.
I would say, too, that one of his strengths was working with the district attorney's office in the city of El Paso.
In fact, when he retired, the city attorney's office, who relied on Jonathan for planning and zoning law interpretations, the district attorney's office did give John a special award

plaque for his service to them because of his knowledge and his willingness to share his knowledge of municipal law zoning law with them well john was very active in aip and was successful in pulling together several regional conferences as well as the texas chapter conference
here several years ago, which was, as I recall, one of the most enjoyable chapter conferences within living memory.
Yes, wasn't he president of the Southwest Planners Group?
I think he was.
I'm not quite sure.
Yes, he was.
And he got the New Mexico planners interested in the Southwestern Gulf Planning Group, too, because they didn't seem to have any
tie to any professional regional group, and he felt they should be a part of the whole planning picture for the Southwest.
Yes, he enjoyed all his many contacts with planning conferences throughout the Southwest and made every effort to go to New Orleans and to go to Atlanta and to go to Albuquerque
College Station.
College Station?
Dallas.
Whenever he could, get away.
He went to American Institute of Planners meetings, American Association of Planning Officials, and I think to become a lifetime member of both organizations, as I recall.
If you can think of anything more when the transcription of this reaches you, you can add that to it, or if there's something that you would prefer to have deleted, you can do that as well.
So thank you very much for your time.
I appreciate it, and APA appreciates it.
I'm honored.
Good morning.
This is March 16th.
We're at Ed Hamlin's house in El Paso.
Ed worked for quite a few years for the planning department and is a native of El Paso.
He has a unique perspective on planning in El Paso.
The interviewer is Robert Cornish, as has been the case with
Ann Cunningham, Nestor Valencia yesterday.
Okay, Ed, let's proceed with the history of planning in El Paso.
I won't ask you questions regarding dates of things and that sort of thing, but from your point of view,

Why don't you first of all consider the first half dozen or so events that you feel were the most important in terms of planning in El Paso that might have impacted planning and might have changed the nature of planning in El Paso?
I think we could first perhaps categorize some events that were important in the overall growth and development of the city.
kind of its reasons for the economic livelihood and why it's here.
And then sort through from that to some of the events that had true plans and evidence.
Sounds good.
The city itself, it has a human settlement area.
It has a long history.
Back in the days of the Spanish explorers, this was a highway route between Chihuahua and Santa Fe.
It being approximately halfway between being located next to a river in an arable valley and having a reputation of being a year-round snow-free pass through the mountains has its name.
The settlement grew up in this area.
That would be the first reason there was a human settlement here at all.
The growth of the American settlement was very limited until
The railroads came in 1881.

The second thing that began to spur up, the next most significant thing that began to spur the growth of the community here, particularly on the American side, was the Mexican Revolution that occurred during the early teens of the century that caused a tremendous flight of Mexican citizens who were on the wrong side of the
This early growth, the latter part of the 19th and early part of the 20th century, had set much of the form of the central core of the city.
It was during this period that the thinking of the white city, the early city planning movement, began to reach as far as El Paso.
And typical of the kind of thinking which was prevalent at the time, there was a plan.
There was a plan for all time that was prepared for the area by a consultant, William Kessler, a man of some notoriety within the profession.

It's interesting in a sense to go back to that early plan and see many of the elements that continue to have relevance and meaning to the city in terms of its physical form that were included in that plan.
The period which followed, particularly going into the Depression, was a period when the city's growth slowed down considerably.
There was very little of any population growth during that period.
El Paso at the time, say 1920, was the biggest city between Dallas and Los Angeles, or at least both to that.
It watched its neighboring communities grow and prosper while they tended to stagnate.

The thing that, the element that began to, again, causing a change in the economic dynamics of the city, I suppose, would be the advent of the use of Fort Bliss, a military fort here, for the aerospace research, particularly in the postwar period.
that together with the military populations which are brought through here, some of which chose to later settle down in this area.
The city has been since 1950 on a rather dynamic growth cycle.

Going back to what elements within the growth would be significant from a planning perspective, early decisions that were made regarding the city's form, the early town maps and things like that were prepared, were done by surveys, as they would have been
as they would have been.

The pattern of the city, perhaps almost owing to its location in the southwestern region, there was a town square created almost as though it had been a Spanish colonial thinking of a town plaza with the governor's mansion around there.
The city didn't have that heritage, but it picked up that form and element from
from neighboring examples, particularly in the older communities that trace the Spanish heritage.
So it wasn't directly modeled after the law of the Indies?
No, it was not directly modeled after that.
Incidentally, for whoever's trying to transcribe that, they're sandblasting my porch right now, and you may have some difficulty hearing me.
That doesn't need to be printed.
No.

Some of the elements from the Kessler plan that became significant that set part of the form of the city, some of the parks that were envisioned in that plan, some of the thinking that accompanied that plan in terms of trying to bring about the identity of the community through some of its resources that would include taking advantage of the bluffs that
offered spectators.
